column96: San Diego County realized the only way to ease congestion was to widen their highways - they have done so on the 15, and traffic is manageable on that highway. King County refuses to widen roads, and instead takes away lanes ... frustrating, to say the least. I have lived here for 13 years, and traffic has gotten worse and worse. The toll roads do not ease congestion; in fact they make congestion worse for those not in the toll lane and on arterial roads. Paying $10 tolls is, quite frankly, out of my price range. I am single, and I work for a non-profit. Property taxes are skyrocketing, and I cannot afford paying up to $10 to drive on a road that I am already paying taxes on. It used to take me 20 to 30 minutes to get to my parents' house (Kingsgate to Lynnwood), even with traffic. It now takes 35 or more minutes to do the same journey. This is ancedotal, but a coworker, who drives from Lynnwood to Redmond every day, confirmed that her commute is much worse since the toll lanes were installed. For those who are wealthy, it is not a hardship to pay up to $10 per trip; but I should not have to pay that cost to see my parents or to go to the doctor, especially since my taxes already pay for this road.
column97: Not much.  Seriously. People illegally cut in and out of them, making them an added danger to motorists.  They are ridiculously expensive, at times; they cater to the elite of society - people who can afford to pay will while those who cannot sit in the traffic. Granted, you have pulled in a boatload of money from the tolls (isn't that always the reason behind such "time saving" systems), but where is that money going? The roads aren't being improved. And, "best" of all, people, who pay to drive in them for a faster way to get where they need to go, still sit in traffic (Kingsgate to Lynnwood).

column97: The express toll lanes make total sense BUT the execution of them for I405 is extremely poor.  I'm happy to pay tolls, as well as carpool, but there MUST be many more entrance points (the location and number of exit points is fine).  There seems to be no reason not to add more entrance points, since the scanner doesn't need to scan until the car LEAVES the carpool (it can determine at what point the car ENTERED based on previous scanner locations not having picked them up).  PLEASE FIX THIS, the current design has created a nightmare for local traffic around Kirkland and Bellevue areas.  Longer distance trips are shorter or same amount of time (e.g. my trips from/to Lynnwood), but more local trips have gone WAY up, negating all value to the Express Toll Lanes for those who use it the most (multiple times daily).

column96: Do you like having the option to use the express toll lanes when you need a faster trip? Yes - if they were truly faster trips. Many a times even after paying the toll, we don't get the promised minimum speed of 40 miles per hour. Tolls are per slots/lengths of the road. So, customers are paying multiple tolls per single work trip. If you look at any other states, these toll rates are comparatively quite expensive and insane while promised value (speed) is almost impossible to deliver. Specially, we have some safety issues because people do cross lanes even though it's a hard line. One option may be to provide cheaper single toll lane and only for longer length trips. Shorter length toll lane use  should be discouraged by how they get charged.

column96: The general idea is that when the normal lanes get traffic the toll goes up (makes sense).  However, what happens when the traffic piles up in the toll lane and the traffic is now moving the same speed in all lanes (toll and non toll lanes)?  You get a ton of unhappy toll paying people.  This is the one negative thing about the toll lane.  I've paid over 10$ at times to sit in traffic that is slower then the non-toll lanes.  This makes absolutely no sense and since you can't leave the toll lanes at anytime you get stuck and you paying to be stuck... You need to fix this somehow.  I don't care what the solution is, just make it so I'm not paying to sit in traffic.  The way it is now doesn't work at all when traffic builds up in the toll lane. Maybe make the toll lane free when the traffic is the same speed in all lanes.  Basically only charge when the lane is actually faster (proven somehow, by analytic live data).  I think it would also help if the toll lane was two lanes all the way north to I5 connection.  However you can't take away a lane from non-toll lanes as that would just make traffic worse all around.  I want a newly built lane, or widen the freeway overall and add more lanes that way.

column96: The tool lanes are a joke! How much of my $20 daily toll actually goes to improving the highway or is even funneled back into local communities and government? My understanding is that some ~70% of my toll goes to the company who installed and operates the equipment, and they're located in Texas and have no concerns with traffic in the greater Seattle area. It's a luxury for the middle to high end households that further opresses the poor. Not to mention, the areas where drivers are allowed to enter/exit toll lanes are CONSTANTLY congested because of drivers quickly merging to and from toll lanes to their exits, i.e. they further congest the regular lanes. In one example, in the 2 lanes through Bothell I saw a vehicle enter the freeway, get into the left regular lane, and then STOP in the left lane for ~10s until they found an opening to squeeze  into the toll lane -- how does that at all solve our traffic problem?! Not to mention, who thought it'd be a good idea to reduce the 405 in Bothell down to 2 regular lanes to install a toll lane?! How does that solve the traffic problem? I bought a motorcycle after spending $100 a week in tolls, and now I risk my life on the daily to get a free toll pass. Thanks WSDOT, greedy Bellevue Square owner, and toll company out of Texas for further wrecking traffic in the greater Seattle area.

column96: Perhaps find a way to ticket those drivers that attempt to cheat the system by crossing double white lines to enter/leave the express toll lanes between toll points. I understand sometimes people are confused about when to exit if they think they can't leave the lanes in time to make their off-ramp to their destination, or even because they've made a mistake getting into the express toll lane. But drivers that weave in and out on purpose create a safety hazard. More traffic cams??   I really like having two express toll lanes in heavily congested areas (i.e. SB between Bothell and Bellevue) to allow for slower moving traffic looking to exit toll lanes, and faster moving traffic on the left. It would be nice to extend this idea to the full length of the express toll lanes in both directions (I know there isn't always space to widen the road).  Either way, I'm generally happy with the express toll lanes. Nice work, guys.
